        "Patient Summary: A 67-year-old male with ESRD on hemodialysis, CAD (s/p DES), DM2, and hypertension was admitted for chest pain and evaluation for active tuberculosis (TB). His course was significant for an acute right MCA ischemic stroke occurring during hemodialysis on hospital day 2, for which he received intravenous tPA.\n\nKey Diagnostic Results:\n- Neurology: Brain CT perfusion and follow-up MRI confirmed an acute infarct in the right posterior frontal lobe (precentral gyrus) with no intracranial hemorrhage. CTA revealed generalized atherosclerotic disease and 65% stenosis of the left internal carotid artery.\n- Cardiology: Myocardial infarction was ruled out with serial troponins and flat CK-MB. Transthoracic Echocardiogram (TTE) demonstrated a preserved LVEF (>55%) and mild LVH; a saline bubble study was negative for ASD or PFO.\n- Infectious Disease: Active TB was ruled out via three negative sputum Acid-Fast Bacilli (AFB) smears and cultures.\n- Laboratory/Imaging: Baseline creatinine (5.9\u201310.9 mg/dL) and mild anemia (Hgb 10.6\u201312.2 g/dL) were consistent with ESRD. Initial pulmonary edema and pleural effusions seen on CXR resolved with fluid management.\n\nClinical Outcome and Management: Following tPA, the patient showed significant improvement, progressing from flaccid left-sided paralysis to 4+/5 motor strength bilaterally. At discharge, he remained alert with mild expressive aphasia and left facial drooping. Management focused on secondary stroke prevention (Aspirin 325mg, Atorvastatin 80mg) and blood pressure control (Lisinopril, Carvedilol). He was discharged home in stable condition, ambulatory with assistance, with orders for outpatient Physical, Occupational, and Speech Therapy, and a scheduled outpatient TEE.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
