        "Significant Results:\n- Laboratory Findings: Renal function tests were consistently abnormal, with Blood Urea Nitrogen (BUN) peaking at 70 mg/dL and Creatinine at 10.9 mg/dL, consistent with ESRD. Hematology showed chronic anemia (Hemoglobin 10.6\u201312.2 g/dL) and episodes of mild leukopenia (WBC 3.6\u20133.7 K/uL). Blood glucose was elevated, peaking at 147 mg/dL. Electrolytes revealed hyperphosphatemia (up to 6.8 mg/dL) and an elevated anion gap (up to 25). Cardiac biomarkers (Troponin-T 0.04\u20130.05 ng/mL) remained flat, ruling out acute myocardial infarction. Microbiology: Three sputum Acid-Fast Bacilli (AFB) smears and cultures were negative, ruling out active TB.\n- Imaging & Diagnostics: \n1. CT Brain Perfusion: Showed right MCA territory ischemia (penumbra) in the superior right frontal lobe and 65% stenosis of the left proximal internal carotid artery (ICA).\n2. Non-Contrast Head CT: Revealed new focal hypodensity in the right frontal lobe corresponding to evolving infarction.\n3. MRI Head: Confirmed acute infarct in the right posterior frontal lobe (precentral gyrus) and chronic small vessel ischemic disease.\n4. EKG: Showed Right Bundle Branch Block (RBBB) and Left Ventricular Hypertrophy (LVH).\n5. TTE & Bubble Study: Preserved LVEF (>55%), moderate left atrial dilation, and no evidence of ASD or PFO.\n6. Chest X-ray: Initially showed mild pulmonary edema, bilateral small pleural effusions, and atelectasis, which improved after dialysis.\n\nDischarge Summary:\nPatient: 67-year-old male.\nReason for Hospitalization: Initially admitted for pleuritic chest pain, productive cough, and night sweats (TB rule-out). \nHospital Course: On the second hospital day, during hemodialysis, the patient developed acute flaccid left upper extremity paralysis, facial droop, and aphasia. A 'Code Stroke' was triggered. CT imaging confirmed a right MCA territory ischemic penumbra. IV tPA was administered within the therapeutic window. He was monitored in the ICU and later transitioned to the floor. His motor strength significantly improved to 4+/5, and aphasia began to resolve. Active TB was ruled out via serial negative sputum studies. Chest pain and pulmonary edema were managed with optimized fluid removal during dialysis.\nDischarge Status: The patient is ambulatory with the assistance of a walker/cane, mentally clear, and coherent. Left-sided facial droop and mild expressive aphasia persist but are improved.\nDischarge Diagnoses: Acute Cerebral Infarct (Right MCA), ESRD on Hemodialysis, Type II Diabetes Mellitus, CAD, Chronic Anemia, and Hypertension.\nMajor Medications: Aspirin 325 mg daily, Atorvastatin 80 mg daily, Lisinopril 20 mg BID, Carvedilol 25 mg BID, and Tramadol (PRN for headache).\nFollow-up: Outpatient TEE is required to further evaluate for embolic sources. Appointments are scheduled for Neurology, Cardiology, Primary Care, and outpatient Physical/Occupational/Speech therapy.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
